#!/bin/bash

# Display OSI Model Layers and Corresponding Protocols and Attacks
cat << EOF
The OSI (Open Systems Interconnection) model is a conceptual framework used to understand and implement networking protocols. Below is a fact-checked and improved version of the table:

### OSI Model Layers and Corresponding Protocols and Attacks

#### Physical Layer (Layer 1)
---------------------------
* **Protocols:** Ethernet, Wi-Fi, PPP (Point-to-Point Protocol)
* **Attacks:** Eavesdropping, jamming, spoofing, tampering with cables or wireless signals

#### Data Link Layer (Layer 2)
---------------------------
* **Protocols:** Ethernet, Wi-Fi, PPP, HDLC (High-Level Data-Link Control)
* **Attacks:** MAC spoofing, ARP spoofing, MAC flooding, man-in-the-middle attacks

#### Network Layer (Layer 3)
-------------------------
* **Protocols:** IP (Internet Protocol), ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol), RIP (Routing Information Protocol), OSPF (Open Shortest Path First)
* **Attacks:** IP spoofing, DNS spoofing, DDoS (Distributed Denial-of-Service) attacks, routing attacks

#### Transport Layer (Layer 4)
---------------------------
* **Protocols:** TCP (Transmission Control Protocol), UDP (User  Datagram Protocol), SCTP (Stream Control Transmission Protocol)
* **Attacks:** SYN Flood, Smurf attacks, TCP Spoofing, fragmentation attacks

#### Session Layer (Layer 5)
-------------------------
* **Protocols:** NetBIOS, SSH (Secure Shell), Telnet
* **Attacks:** Session hijacking, session replay, session fixation, cookie poisoning

#### Presentation Layer (Layer 6)
------------------------------
* **Protocols:** SSL/TLS (Secure Sockets Layer/Transport Layer Security), MIME (Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions)
* **Attacks:** Man-in-the-middle attacks, SSL stripping, padding oracle attacks, data compression attacks

#### Application Layer (Layer 7)
-----------------------------
* **Protocols:** HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol), FTP (File Transfer Protocol), SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol), DNS (Domain Name System)
* **Attacks:** SQL injection, cross-site scripting (XSS), cross-site request forgery (CSRF), buffer overflow attacks, command injection attacks

EOF
